# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: exhaust-system
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] The **acoustoelastic effect** is how the sound velocities (both longitudinal and shear wave velocities) of an elastic material change if subjected to an initial static stress field.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] This is a non-linear effect of the constitutive relation between mechanical stress and finite strain in a material of continuous mass.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] In classical linear elasticity theory small deformations of most elastic materials can be described by a linear relation between the applied stress and the resulting strain.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] This relationship is commonly known as the generalised Hooke's law.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] The linear elastic theory involves second order elastic constants (e.g. $\lambda$ and $\mu$ ) and yields constant longitudinal and shear sound velocities in an elastic material, not affected by an applied stress.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] The acoustoelastic effect on the other hand include higher order expansion of the constitutive relation (non-linear elasticity theory) between the applied stress and resulting strain, which yields longitudinal and shear sound velocities dependent of the stress state of the material.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] In the limit of an unstressed material the sound velocities of the linear elastic theory are reproduced.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] The acoustoelastic effect was investigated as early as 1925 by Brillouin.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] He found that the propagation velocity of acoustic waves would decrease proportional to an applied hydrostatic pressure.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] However, a consequence of his theory was that sound waves would stop propagating at a sufficiently large pressure.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] This paradoxical effect was later shown to be caused by the incorrect assumptions that the elastic parameters were not affected by the pressure.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] In 1937 Francis Dominic Murnaghan presented a mathematical theory extending the linear elastic theory to also include finite deformation in elastic isotropic materials.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] This theory included three third-order elastic constants l , m , and n .
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] In 1953 Huges and Kelly used the theory of Murnaghan in their experimental work to establish numerical values for higher order elastic constants for several elastic materials including Polystyrene, Armco iron, and Pyrex, subjected to hydrostatic pressure and uniaxial compression.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] The acoustoelastic effect is an effect of finite deformation of non-linear elastic materials.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] A modern comprehensive account of this can be found in.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] This book treats the application of the non-linear elasticity theory and the analysis of the mechanical properties of solid materials capable of large elastic deformations.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] The special case of the acoustoelastic theory for a compressible isotropic hyperelastic material, like polycrystalline steel, is reproduced and shown in this text from the non-linear elasticity theory as presented by Ogden.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] However, the work done by the stresses may depend on the path the deformation takes.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] Therefore, a Cauchy elastic material has a non-conservative structure, and the stress cannot be derived from a scalar elastic potential function.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] The special case of Cauchy elastic materials where the work done by the stresses is independent of the path of deformation is referred to as a Green elastic or hyperelastic material.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] Such materials are conservative and the stresses in the material can be derived by a scalar elastic potential, more commonly known as the Strain energy density function.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] The constitutive relation between the stress and strain can be expressed in different forms based on the chosen stress and strain forms.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] W is the strain energy density function for a hyperelastic material and have been defined per unit volume rather than per unit mass since this avoids the need of multiplying the right hand side with the mass density $\rho _{0}$ of the reference configuration.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] The symmetry of $E_{ij}=E_{ji}$ together with the scalar strain energy density function W implies that the second order moduli $C_{ijkl}$ have the following symmetry: $C_{ijkl}=C_{jikl}=C_{ijlk},$ which reduce the number of independent elastic constants from 81 to 36.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] In addition the power expansion implies that the second order moduli also have the major symmetry $C_{ijkl}=C_{klij},$ which further reduce the number of independent elastic constants to 21.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] The same arguments can be used for the third order elastic moduli $C_{ijklmn}$ .
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] These symmetries also allows the elastic moduli to be expressed by the Voigt notation (i.e. $C_{ijkl}=C_{IJ}$ and $C_{ijklmn}=C_{IJK}$ ).
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] Assuming that a small dynamic (acoustic) deformation disturb an already statically stressed material the acoustoelastic effect can be regarded as the effect on a small deformation superposed on a larger finite deformation (also called the small-on-large theory).
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] Let us define three states of a given material point.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] In the reference (un-stressed) state the point is defined by the coordinate vector ${\boldsymbol {X}}$ while the same point has the coordinate vector ${\boldsymbol {x}}$ in the static initially stressed state (i.e. under the influence of an applied pre-stress).
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] Finally, assume that the material point under a small dynamic disturbance (acoustic stress field) have the coordinate vector ${\boldsymbol {x'}}$ .
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] The wave velocities can be determined by the characteristic equation $\det({\boldsymbol {Q}}({\boldsymbol {N}})-\rho _{0}c^{2}{\boldsymbol {I}})=0,$ where $\det$ is the determinant and ${\boldsymbol {I}}$ is the identity matrix.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] For a hyperelastic material ${\boldsymbol {Q}}({\boldsymbol {N}})$ is symmetric (but not in general), and the eigenvalues ( $\rho _{0}c^{2}$ ) are thus real.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] For the wave velocities to also be real the eigenvalues need to be positive.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] If this is the case, three mutually orthogonal real plane waves exist for the given propagation direction ${\boldsymbol {N}}$ .
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] The polarization ${\boldsymbol {m}}={\boldsymbol {N}}$ corresponds to a longitudinal wave where the particle motion is parallel to the propagation direction (also referred to as a compressional wave).
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] The two polarizations where ${\boldsymbol {m}}\cdot {\boldsymbol {N}}=0$ corresponds to transverse waves where the particle motion is orthogonal to the propagation direction (also referred to as shear waves).
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] The constants $\lambda$ and $\mu$ are the second order elastic moduli better known as the Lamé parameters, while $A,B,$ and C are the third order elastic moduli introduced by, which are alternative but equivalent to $l,m,$ and n introduced by Murnaghan.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] Historically different selection of these third order elastic constants have been used, and some of the variations is shown in Table 1.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] Here $l_{i}$ signifies the current (deformed) length of the cuboid side i and where the ratio between the length of the sides in the current and reference configuration are denoted by $\lambda _{i}\equiv l_{i}/L_{i}$ called the principal stretches.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] For an isotropic material this corresponds to a deformation without any rotation (See polar decomposition of the deformation gradient tensor where ${\boldsymbol {F}}={\boldsymbol {RU}}={\boldsymbol {VR}}$ and the rotation ${\boldsymbol {R}}={\boldsymbol {I}}$ ).
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] This can be described through spectral representation by the principal stretches $\lambda _{i}$ as eigenvalues, or equivalently by the elongations $e_{i}$ .
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] For a uniaxial tension in the $x_{1}$ -direction ( $P_{11}>0$ we assume that the $e_{1}$ increase by some amount.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] For isotropic symmetry the lateral elongations (or contractions) must also be equal (i.e. $e_{2}=e_{3}$ ).
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] The range corresponds to the range from total lateral contraction ( $e_{2}=e_{3}=-1$ , which is non-physical), and to no change in the lateral dimensions ( $e_{2}=e_{3}=0$ ).
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] It is noted that theoretically the range could be expanded to values large than 0 corresponding to an increase in lateral dimensions as a result of increase in axial dimension.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] However, very few materials (called auxetic materials) exhibit this property.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] If the strong ellipticity condition ( $B_{ijkl}N_{j}N_{l}m_{i}m_{k}>0$ ) holds, three orthogonally polarization directions ( ${\boldsymbol {m}}$ will give a non-zero and real sound velocity for a given propagation direction ${\boldsymbol {N}}$ .
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] The following will derive the sound velocities for óne selection of applied uniaxial tension, propagation direction, and an orthonormal set of polarization vectors.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] To be able to measure the sound velocity, and more specifically the change in sound velocity, in a material subjected to some stress state, one can measure the velocity of an acoustic signal propagating through the material in question.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] There are several methods to do this but all of them use one of two physical relations of the sound velocity.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] The first relation is related to the time it takes a signal to propagate from one point to another (typically the distance between two acoustic transducers or two times the distance from one transducer to a reflective surface).
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] This is often referred to as "Time-of-flight" (TOF) measurements, and use the relation $c={\frac {d}{t}}$ where d is the distance the signal travels and t is the time it takes to travel this distance.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] The second relation is related to the inverse of the time, the frequency, of the signal.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] The relation here is $c=f\lambda$ where f is the frequency of the signal and $\lambda$ is the wave length.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] The measurements using the frequency as measurand use the phenomenon of acoustic resonance where n number of wave lengths match the length over which the signal resonate.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] Both these methods are dependent on the distance over which it measure, either directly as in the Time-of-flight, or indirectly through the matching number of wavelengths over the physical extent of the specimen which resonate.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] In general there are two ways to set up a transducer system to measure the sound velocity in a solid.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] One is a setup with two or more transducers where one is acting as a transmitter, while the other(s) is acting as a receiver.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] The other type of setup is often called a *pulse-echo* system.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] Here one transducer is placed in the vicinity of the specimen acting both as transmitter and receiver.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] This requires a reflective interface where the generated signal can be reflected back toward the transducer which then act as a receiver recording the reflected signal.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] See ultrasonic testing for some measurement systems.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] As explained above, a set of three orthonormal polarizations ( ${\boldsymbol {m}}$ ) of the particle motion exist for a given propagation direction ${\boldsymbol {N}}$ in a solid.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] Thus it is possible to measure the sound velocity of waves with all three polarizations through either time dependent or frequency dependent measurement setups depending on the selection of transducer types.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] However, if the transducer can not be fixated to the test specimen a coupling medium is needed to transmit the acoustic energy from the transducer to the specimen.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] Water or gels are often used as this coupling medium.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] Such shear waves are then converted back to longitudinal waves at the solid/fluid surface propagating back through the fluid to the recording transducer enabling the measurement of shear wave velocities as well through a coupling medium.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] As the industry strives to reduce maintenance and repair costs, non-destructive testing of structures becomes increasingly valued both in production control and as a means to measure the utilization and condition of key infrastructure.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] There are several measurement techniques to measure stress in a material.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] However, techniques using optical measurements, magnetic measurements, X-ray diffraction, and neutron diffraction are all limited to measuring surface or near surface stress or strains.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] Acoustic waves propagate with ease through materials and provide thus a means to probe the interior of structures, where the stress and strain level is important for the overall structural integrity.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] seismology study the propagation of elastic waves through the Earth and is used in e.g. earthquake studies and in mapping the Earth's interior.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] The interior of the Earth is subjected to different pressures, and thus the acoustic signals may pass through media in different stress states.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] The acoustoelastic theory may thus be of practical interest where nonlinear wave behaviour may be used to estimate geophysical properties.
[src:exhaust-system/acoustoelastic-effect] Other applications may be in medical sonography and elastography measuring the stress or pressure level in relevant elastic tissue types (e.g., ), enhancing non-invasive diagnostics.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] The parts, accessories, etc. for sale may or may not be manufactured by the OEM.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] The aftermarket encompasses parts for replacement, collision, appearance, and performance.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] The aftermarket provides a wide variety of parts of varying qualities and prices for nearly all vehicle makes and models.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] Consumers have the option of repairing their vehicles themselves (the "do-it-yourself" or "DIY" segment) or can take the vehicle to a professional repair facility (the "do-it-for me" or "DIFM" segment).
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] The aftermarket helps keep vehicles on the road by providing consumers the choice of where they want their vehicles serviced, maintained, or customized.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] The United States automotive aftermarket covering light-, medium- and heavy-duty vehicles is estimated to be worth $516 billion (2025).
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] The United States automotive aftermarket contribute more than 1.9% to GDP according to Hedges & Company.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] The aftermarket employs 4.9 million people who work at manufacturers, distributors, retailers and repair shops.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] In the United States, online sales of aftermarket accessories have increased year over year over traditional brick and mortar stores.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] In fact, according to Hedges & Company, "Total online eCommerce revenue for automotive parts and accessories in 2024 was at $42.4 billion in the US." That includes $21.7 billion from first-party 1P eCommerce websites and $20.7 billion from third-party 3P marketplaces.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] Singapore, which does not have a domestic automobile industry, is an especially important destination for businesses exporting automotive parts and accessories due to its high automobile turnover stemming from the peculiarities of its driving laws.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] High automobile turnover and the preference for new parts means that the market for remanufactured and reconditioned auto parts is very small.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] Combined with a high demand for "accessories, car-care products, prestige items, and new spare parts," Singapore's automotive aftermarket is large.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] In fact, Singapore has become a major automotive *components* manufacturing base, as several leading multinational corporations (MNCs) have established international procurement offices as well as their Southeast Asia distribution centers.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] In Canada, the automotive aftermarket is a C$19.4 billion industry that employs about 420,000 people.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] In Australia, the automotive aftermarket industry in 2013 was estimated to generate a AUD$5.2 billion turnover, with 21000 staff, and 1400 manufacturers.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] in Europe, the total volume of Independent Aftermarket (IAM) amounted to 127 billion Euros in 2015 (end-user prices without labor and tax).
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] At that moment there were 54 parts traders with annual turnover over 100 mio Euros in Europe, 6 of them exceeded 1 billion Euros.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] Meeting platform for the international automotive aftermarket is the B2B trade fair Automechanika Dubai which takes place every two years in Frankfurt.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] At last edition the hot topics were connected cars, autonomous driving, alternative drives and the workshop of the future.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] Among online retailers, Amazon.com and eBay Motors are the largest sellers of aftermarket parts and accessories in the U.S. by both units sold and revenue, and are expected to grow 25% in 2014, far outstripping traditional chain stores.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] As DIY parts sales soften at the retail counter, chain stores have pushed themselves into the DIFM commercial business, eating into distributors’ and wholesalers’ market share.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] Since 2007, DIY sales at the chain stores have fallen a total of 3% to 5%, while commercial sales have brought in a double-digit sales increase.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] AutoZone’s DIFM sales in 2013 alone increased over 13%.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] Online sales of auto parts and accessories in the United States, including 3P marketplaces, are estimated at $42.4 billion in 2024.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] Automobile manufacturers have attempted to hinder or suppress automotive aftermarket sales by means of copyright or patent infringement litigation.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] For example, in *British Leyland Motor Corp. v Armstrong Patents Co.* in the UK, the House of Lords decided in 1986 that Leyland could not claim copyright infringement in order to prevent the aftermarket sale of replacement tailpipes to purchasers of those motor cars.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] In 2005 Harley-Davidson filed a patent and trademark infringement lawsuit against two aftermarket engine manufacturers producing drop-in replacements for Harley's engines, namely S&S Cycle and Delkron, Inc.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] Harley accused S&S and Delkron of copying parts for Twin Cam engines and using Harley trademarks without permission.
[src:exhaust-system/aftermarket-automotive] S&S argued that the suit was without any legal basis, and asserted that "a mutually beneficial relationship existed" between them and Harley.
[src:exhaust-system/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:exhaust-system/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:exhaust-system/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:exhaust-system/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:exhaust-system/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:exhaust-system/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:exhaust-system/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:exhaust-system/air-pollution] Outdoor air pollution comes from burning fossil fuels for electricity and transport, wildfires, some industrial processes, waste management, demolition and agriculture.
[src:exhaust-system/air-pollution] Indoor air pollution is often from burning firewood or agricultural waste for cooking and heating.
[src:exhaust-system/air-pollution] Other sources of air pollution include dust storms and volcanic eruptions.
[src:exhaust-system/air-pollution] Many sources of local air pollution, especially burning fossil fuels, also release greenhouse gases that cause global warming.
[src:exhaust-system/air-pollution] However, air pollution may limit warming locally.
[src:exhaust-system/air-pollution] Air pollution kills 7 to 8 million people each year.
[src:exhaust-system/air-pollution] It is a significant risk factor for a number of diseases, including stroke, heart disease, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), asthma, coronavirus and lung cancer.
[src:exhaust-system/air-pollution] Particulate matter is the most deadly, both for indoor and outdoor air pollution.
[src:exhaust-system/air-pollution] Ozone affects crops, and forests are damaged by the pollution that causes acid rain.
[src:exhaust-system/air-pollution] Overall, the World Bank has estimated that welfare losses (premature deaths) and productivity losses (lost labor) caused by air pollution cost the world economy over $8 trillion per year.
[src:exhaust-system/air-pollution] Various technologies and strategies reduce air pollution.
[src:exhaust-system/air-pollution] Key approaches include clean cookers, fire protection, improved waste management, dust control, industrial scrubbers, electric vehicles and renewable energy.
[src:exhaust-system/air-pollution] National air quality laws have often been effective, notably the 1956 Clean Air Act in Britain and the 1963 US Clean Air Act.
[src:exhaust-system/air-pollution] International efforts have had mixed results: the Montreal Protocol almost eliminated harmful ozone-depleting chemicals, while international action on climate change has been less successful.
[src:exhaust-system/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:exhaust-system/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:exhaust-system/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:exhaust-system/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:exhaust-system/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:exhaust-system/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:exhaust-system/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:exhaust-system/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:exhaust-system/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:exhaust-system/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:exhaust-system/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:exhaust-system/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] An **alternator** is a type of electric generator used in modern automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] As silicon-diode rectifiers became widely available and affordable, the alternator gradually replaced the dynamo.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] This was encouraged by the increasing electrical power required for cars in this period, with increasing loads from larger headlamps, electric wipers, heated rear windows, and other accessories.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] The modern type of vehicle alternators were first used in military applications during World War II, to power radio equipment on specialist vehicles.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] After the war, other vehicles with high electrical demands — such as ambulances and radio taxis — could also be fitted with optional alternators.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Alternators were first introduced as standard equipment on a production car by the Chrysler Corporation on the Valiant in 1960, several years ahead of Ford and General Motors.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Some early automobiles, like the Ford Model T, used a different sort of charging system: an engine-driven magneto which generated low-voltage alternating current that was supplied to trembler coils, which provided the high voltage needed to generate ignition sparks.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] The Model T incorporated its magneto into the engine flywheel.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] The first Model Ts used the magneto solely for the trembler coil ignition.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Beginning with the 1915 model year, Ford added electric headlights, also powered by the magneto.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] The magneto circuit was strictly AC, with no battery included.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] (There was a switch on the ignition coils to use a battery instead, which could be helpful when starting in cold weather, but Ford neither provided a battery nor did it encourage the use of one before it introduced an electric starter in 1919.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Starting in the 1919 model year, Ford upgraded the Model T to include an electric starter, which was standard for some models and optional for others.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] This starter installation also included a battery, charged by a conventional dynamo, and the lights were now powered by the battery.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] However, the flywheel magneto still powered the ignition, and since models without the starter had no battery, they continued to use magneto-powered lights.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Alternators have several advantages over direct-current generators (dynamos).
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] A set of rectifiers (diode bridge) is required to convert alternating current (AC) to DC.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] To provide direct current with low ripple, a polyphase winding is used and the pole-pieces of the rotor are shaped (claw-pole).
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators are usually belt-driven at 2–3 times crankshaft speed, speeds that could cause a commutator to fly apart in a generator.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] The alternator runs at various RPM (which varies the frequency) since it is driven by the engine, regardless of direction of rotation.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] This is not a problem because the alternating current is rectified to DC.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Alternator regulators are also simpler than those for generators.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Generator regulators require a cutout relay to isolate the output coils (the armature) from the battery at low speed; that isolation is provided by the alternator rectifier diodes.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Also, most generator regulators include a current limiter; alternators are inherently current-limited.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] The claw pole design produces an AC waveform that is more efficiently rectified than a sine wave.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Despite their names, both 'DC generators' (or 'dynamos') and 'alternators' initially produce alternating current.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] In a so-called 'DC generator', this AC current is generated in the rotating armature, and then converted to DC by the commutator and brushes.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] In an 'alternator', the AC current is generated in the stationary stator, and then is converted to DC by the rectifiers (diodes).
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger vehicle and light truck alternators use Lundahl or 'claw-pole' field construction.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] This uses a shaped iron core on the rotor to produce a multi-pole field from a single coil winding.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] The poles of the rotor look like fingers of two hands interlocked with each other.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] The coil is mounted axially inside this and field current is supplied by slip rings and carbon brushes.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] These alternators have their field and stator windings cooled by axial airflow, produced by an external fan attached to the drive belt pulley.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Modern vehicles now use the compact alternator layout.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] This is electrically and magnetically similar, but has improved air cooling.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Better cooling permits more power from a smaller machine.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] The casing has distinctive radial vent slots at each end and now encloses the fan.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Two fans are used, one at each end, and the airflow is semi-radial, entering axially and leaving radially outwards.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] The stator windings now consist of a dense central band where the iron core and copper windings are tightly packed, and end bands where the windings are more exposed for better heat transfer.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] The closer core spacing from the rotor improves magnetic efficiency.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] The smaller, enclosed fans produce less noise, particularly at higher machine speeds.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Alternators can also be water-cooled in cars.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Larger vehicles may have field coil alternators similar to larger machines.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] The windings of a 3 phase alternator may be connected using either the *delta* or *star* (*wye*) connection regime set-up.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Brushless versions of these type alternators are also common in larger machinery such as highway trucks and earthmoving machinery.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] With two oversized shaft bearings as the only wearing parts, these can provide extremely long and reliable service, even exceeding the engine overhaul intervals.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators require a voltage regulator which operates by modulating the small field current to produce a constant voltage at the battery terminals.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Early designs (c.1960s–1970s) used a discrete device mounted elsewhere in the vehicle.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Intermediate designs (c.1970s–1990s) incorporated the voltage regulator into the alternator housing.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Modern designs do away with the voltage regulator altogether; voltage regulation is now a function of the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] The field current is much smaller than the output current of the alternator; for example, a 70 A alternator may need only 2-3 A of field current.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] The field current is supplied to the rotor windings by slip rings.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] The low current and relatively smooth slip rings ensure greater reliability and longer life than that obtained by a DC generator with its commutator and higher current being passed through its brushes.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] The field windings are supplied with power from the battery via the ignition switch and regulator.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] A parallel circuit supplies the "charge" warning indicator and is earthed via the regulator (which is why the indicator is on when the ignition is on but the engine is not running).
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Once the engine is running and the alternator is generating power, a diode feeds the field current from the alternator main output equalizing the voltage across the warning indicator which goes off.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] The wire supplying the field current is often referred to as the "exciter" wire.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] The drawback of this arrangement is that if the warning lamp burns out or the "exciter" wire is disconnected, no current reaches the field windings and the alternator will not generate power.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Some warning indicator circuits are equipped with a resistor in parallel with the lamp that permit excitation current to flow if the warning lamp burns out.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] The driver should check that the warning indicator is on when the engine is stopped; otherwise, there might not be any indication of a failure of the belt which may also drive the cooling water pump.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Some alternators will self-excite when the engine reaches a certain speed.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] In recent years, alternator regulators are linked to the vehicle's computer system and various factors including air temperature obtained from the intake air temperature sensor, battery temperature sensor and engine load are evaluated in adjusting the voltage supplied by the alternator.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Older automobiles with minimal lighting may have had an alternator capable of producing only 30 amperes.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger car and light truck alternators are rated around 50–70 A, though higher ratings are becoming more common, especially as there is more load on the vehicle's electrical system with air conditioning, electric power steering and other electrical systems.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators used on buses, heavy equipment or emergency vehicles may produce 300 A.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Semi-trucks usually have alternators which output 140 A.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators may be water-cooled or oil-cooled.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Efficiency of automotive alternators is limited by fan cooling loss, bearing loss, iron loss, copper loss, and the voltage drop in the diode bridges.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Efficiency reduces dramatically at high speeds mainly due to fan resistance.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] At medium speeds efficiency of today's alternators is 70–80%.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] This betters very small high-performance permanent magnet alternators, such as those used for bicycle lighting systems, which achieve an efficiency around 60%.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Larger permanent magnet electric machines (that can operate as motors or alternators) can achieve today much higher efficiencies.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Pellegrino et al., for instance, propose not particularly expensive designs that show ample regions in which efficiency is above 96%.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Large AC generators used in power stations run at carefully controlled speeds and have no constraints on size or weight.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] They have very high efficiencies as high as 98%.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] Hybrid electric vehicles replace the separate alternator and starter motor with one or more combined motor/generator(s) that start the internal combustion engine, provide some or all of the mechanical power to the wheels, and charge a large storage battery.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] When more than one motor/generator is present, as in the Hybrid Synergy Drive used in the Toyota Prius and others, one may operate as a generator and feed the other as a motor, providing an electromechanical path for some of the engine power to flow to the wheels.
[src:exhaust-system/alternator-automotive] These motor/generators have considerably more powerful electronic devices for their control than the automotive alternator described above.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] An **exhaust system** is used to guide reaction exhaust gases away from a controlled combustion inside an engine or stove.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] The entire system conveys burnt gases from the engine and includes one or more **exhaust pipes**.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] An exhaust pipe must be carefully designed to carry toxic and noxious gases away from the users of the machine.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Indoor generators and furnaces can quickly fill an enclosed space with poisonous exhaust gases such as hydrocarbons, carbon monoxide and nitrogen oxides, if they are not properly vented to the outdoors.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Also, the gases from most machines are scorching; the pipe must be heat-resistant and not pass through or near anything that can burn or be damaged by heat.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] A chimney is an exhaust pipe in a stationary structure.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] For the internal combustion engine, it is important to have the exhaust system "tuned" (refer to tuned exhaust) for optimal efficiency.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Also, this should meet the norms of the regulations in each country.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] In most motorcycles, all or most of the exhaust system is visible and may be chrome plated as a display feature.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Aftermarket exhausts may be made from steel, aluminium, titanium, or carbon fiber.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Motorcycle exhausts come in many varieties depending on the type of engine and its intended use.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] A twin-cylinder bike may have independent exhaust sections, as seen in the Kawasaki EX250 (also known as the Ninja 250 in the US, or the GPX 250), or a single exhaust section known as a two-into-one (2-1).
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Four-cylinder machines, super-sport bikes like Kawasaki's ZX series, Honda's CBR series, Yamaha's YZF series, latterly titled R6 and R1, and Suzuki's GSX-R, often have a twin exhaust system.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] A "full system" may be bought as an aftermarket accessory, also called a 4-2-1 or 4–1, depending on its layout.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] In the past, these bikes would come as standard with a single exhaust muffler.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] This practice lasted until the early 2000s when EU noise and pollution regulations effectively forced companies to use other methods to increase the motorcycle's performance.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] In many trucks / lorries, all or most of the exhaust system is visible, often with a vertical exhaust pipe.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Usually, in such trucks, the silencer is surrounded by a perforated metal sheath to avoid people getting burnt from touching the hot silencer.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] This sheath may be chrome plated as a display feature.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Part of the pipe between the engine and the silencer is often flexible metal industrial ducting, which helps to avoid vibration from the engine being transferred into the exhaust system.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Sometimes, a large diesel exhaust pipe is vertical to blow the hot, toxic gas well away from people; in such cases, the end of the exhaust pipe often has a hinged metal flap to stop debris, birds, and rainwater from falling inside.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] In former times, exhaust systems of trucks / lorries in Britain were usually out of sight underneath the chassis.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] In a two-stroke engine, such as that used on dirt bikes, a bulge in the exhaust pipe known as an expansion chamber uses the pressure of the exhaust to create a pump that squeezes more air and fuel into the cylinder during the intake stroke.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] This provides greater power and fuel efficiency.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] In outboard motors, the exhaust system is usually a vertical passage through the engine structure, and to reduce out-of-water noise, it blows out underwater, sometimes through the middle of the propeller.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] In most production engines, the **manifold** is an assembly designed to collect exhaust gas from two or more cylinders into one pipe.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] In stock production cars, manifolds are often made of cast iron.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] They may have material-saving design features such as using the least metal, occupying the least space necessary, or having the lowest production cost.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] These design restrictions often result in a cost-effective design that does not do the most efficient job of venting the gases from the engine.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Inefficiencies generally occur due to the nature of the combustion engine and its cylinders.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Since cylinders fire at different times, exhaust leaves them at different times, and pressure waves from gas emerging from one cylinder might not be completely vacated through the exhaust system when another comes.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] This creates back pressure and restriction in the engine's exhaust system, restricting the engine's performance.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] A **header** is a manifold specifically designed for performance.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] During design, engineers create a manifold without regard to weight or cost but instead for optimal flow of the exhaust gases.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] This design results in a header that is more efficient at **scavenging** the exhaust from the cylinders.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Headers are generally circular steel tubing with bends and folds calculated to make the paths from each cylinder's exhaust port to the common outlet all equal length and joined at narrow angles to encourage pressure waves to flow through the outlet, not back towards other cylinders.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] In a set of **tuned headers** the pipe lengths are carefully calculated to enhance exhaust flow in a particular engine revolutions per minute range.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] A common method of increasing an engine's power output is using upgraded headers.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] The increased power output is often due to a result of a larger cross-section area of the pipes (reducing the resistance on the exhaust gasses) and designing the pipe lengths so that the pressure wave assists in exhaust scavenging.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] For inline-four engines and V8 engines, exhaust manifolds are usually either a 4-2-1 design (where the four pipes merge into two, followed by a separate merge of these two pipes into one) or a 4-1 design (where the four pipes directly merge into one).
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Headers are generally made by aftermarket automotive companies, but sometimes can be bought from the high-performance parts department at car dealerships.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Generally, most car performance enthusiasts buy aftermarket headers made by companies solely focused on producing reliable, cost-effective, well-designed headers specifically for their cars.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Headers can also be custom-designed by a specialty shop.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Due to the advanced materials that some aftermarket headers are made of, this can be expensive.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] An exhaust system can be custom-built for many vehicles and generally is not specific to the car's engine or design except for needing to properly connect solidly to the engine.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] This is usually accomplished by correct sizing in the design stage and selecting a proper gasket type and size for the engine.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Some systems (called **catless** or **de-cat** systems) eliminate the catalytic converter.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] It is a U.S. legal requirement to have a catalytic converter.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Converters may not be removed from a vehicle that is used only for "off-road" driving in the United States.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] The main purpose of a catalytic converter on an automobile is to reduce harmful emissions of hydrocarbons, carbon monoxide, and nitrogen oxides into the atmosphere.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] They work by transforming the polluted exhaust components into water and carbon dioxide.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] There is a light-off temperature from which catalytic converters start to be efficient and work properly.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Catalytic converters can cause back pressure if clogged or not designed for the required flow rate.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] In these situations, upgrading or removal of the catalytic converter can increase power at high revs.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] However, the catalytic converter is vital to the vehicle's emission control systems.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Therefore, a non-standard product can cause a vehicle to be unroadworthy.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] The piping that connects all of the individual components of the exhaust system is called the exhaust pipe.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] If the diameter is too small, power at high RPM will be reduced.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Piping diameter that is too large can reduce torque at low RPM and can cause the exhaust system to be lower to the ground, increasing the risk of it being hit and damaged while the car is moving.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] On cars with two sets of exhaust pipes, a crossover pipe is often used to connect the two pipes.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Typical designs of crossover pipes are a perpendicular pipe ('H-pipe', due to their shape) or angled pipes that slowly merge and separate ('X-pipe').
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Original equipment mufflers typically reduces the noise level from the tailpipe by bouncing sound waves off of the back, front, and sides of the muffler.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] They are designed to meet the maximum allowable noise level required by government regulations.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] However, some original equipment mufflers are a significant source of backpressure.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Glasspack mufflers (also called 'cannons' or 'hotdogs') are straight-through design mufflers that consist of an inner perforated tube, an outer solid tube, and fiberglass sound insulation between the two tubes.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] They often have less back pressure than original equipment mufflers, but are relatively ineffective at reducing sound levels.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Another common type of muffler is the chambered muffler, which consists of a series of concentric or eccentric pipes inside the expansion chamber cavity.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] These pipes allow sound to travel into them and cause the sound waves to bounce off the closed, flat ends of the pipe.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] These reflections partially cancel each other out, reducing the sound level.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Resonators are sections of pipe that expand to a larger diameter and allow the sound waves to reflect off the walls and cancel out, reducing the noise level.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Resonators can be used inside mufflers or as separate components in an exhaust system.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] With trucks, sometimes the silencer is crossways under the front of the cab, and its tailpipe blows sideways to the offside (right side if driving on the left, left side if driving on the right).
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] The end of the final length of the exhaust pipe where it vents to open air, generally the only visible part of the exhaust system part on a vehicle, often ends with a straight or angled cut but may include a decorative tip.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] It frequently has a larger pipe than the rest of the exhaust system.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] This produces a final reduction in pressure and is sometimes used to enhance the car's appearance.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] In the late 1950s, in the United States, manufacturers had a fashion in car styling to form the rear bumper with a hole at each end through which the exhaust would pass.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Many expensive cars (Cadillac, Lincoln, Imperial, Packard) were fitted with this design.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] One justification for this was that luxury cars in those days had such an extended rear overhang that the exhaust pipe scraped the ground when the car traversed ramps.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] The fashion disappeared after customers noted that the rear end of the vehicle is a low-pressure area that collected soot from the exhaust, and its acidic content ate into the chrome-plated rear bumper.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] In some trucks, when the silencer (muffler) is front-to-back under the chassis, the end of the tailpipe turns and blows downwards.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] That protects anyone near a stationary truck from getting a direct blast of the exhaust gas but often raises dust when driving on a dry, dusty surface such as on a building site.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] No intrinsic performance gain to be derived, *per se*, lake pipes evolved a function of practicality.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Body-on-frame chassis architecture ceding to superleggera, unibody, and monocoque archetypes, in tandem with smog abatement legislation rendered lake pipes obsolete as a performance option.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] There is no meaningful performance gain for contemporary vehicles; lake pipes are aesthetic accessories usually chrome-plated.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Some allow the driver to control whether the exhaust gas is routed to the standard exhaust system or through the lake pipes.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Some are equipped with laker caps which, affixed by fasteners at the terminal end of exhaust tips, serve to (1) "cap" the exhaust system when not in use and/or (2) indicate that the presence of lake pipes is merely cosmetic.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] The **Header-back** (or **header back**) is part of the exhaust system from the header outlet to the final vent to open air — everything from the header back.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Header-back systems are generally produced as aftermarket performance systems for cars without turbochargers.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] The **Turbo-back** (or **turbo back**) is part of the exhaust system from the outlet of a turbocharger to the final vent to open air.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Turbo-back systems are generally produced as aftermarket performance systems for cars with turbochargers.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Some turbo-back (and header-back) systems replace stock catalytic converters, while others have less flow restriction.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Cat-back exhaust systems generally use pipes of larger diameters than the stock system.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] To reduce backpressure, the mufflers included in these kits are often glasspacks.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] If the system is engineered more for show than functionality, it may be tuned to enhance the lower sounds from high-RPM low-displacement engines.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Exhaust aftertreatments are devices or methods to meet emission regulations.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Aftermarket exhaust parts can increase peak power by reducing the back pressure of the exhaust system.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] These parts sometimes can void factory warranties, however the European Union *Block Exemption Regulations 1400/2002* prevents manufacturers from rejecting warranty claims if the aftermarket parts are of matching quality and specifications to the original parts.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Many automotive companies offer aftermarket exhaust system upgrades as a subcategory of engine tuning.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] This is often relatively expensive as it usually includes replacing the entire exhaust manifold or other significant components.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] These upgrades, however, can improve engine performance by reducing the exhaust back pressure and reducing the amount of heat from the exhaust being lost into the underbonnet area.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] This reduces the underbonnet temperature and consequently lowers the intake manifold temperature, increasing power.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] This also has a positive side effect of preventing damage to heat-sensitive components.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Backpressure is most commonly reduced by replacing exhaust manifolds with headers, which have smoother bends and normally wider pipe diameters.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Exhaust heat management helps reduce exhaust heat radiating from the exhaust pipe and components.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] One dominant solution to aftermarket upgrades is the use of a ceramic coating applied via thermal spraying as a heat shield.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] This not only reduces heat loss and lessens back pressure, but also provides an effective way to protect the exhaust system from wear and tear, thermal degradation, and corrosion.
[src:exhaust-system/exhaust-system] Tuning can change the noise of the exhaust system, known as *exhaust notes*.
